 These are shared Shipshape declarations. Cite an Article by its title. Two groups by trigger: six Dispositions and three Custody Articles. Dispositions are held at every moment; their trigger is internal, so they must shape every judgment. Custody Articles bind at a legible moment of action: a dispatch, a file write, a seam change. An enforcing runtime enforces the Custody group as hard constraints, within the reach its hooks state; a skill-only agent follows all nine by explicit discipline. Craft that applies at a named moment lives in the agreements, the policies, and the role skills; each Article points to its mechanics.
 
+### Batched retrieval
+
+Every role gathers context through Yoink, never through free-standing shell. A shell call is a round-trip: the role issues one command, waits, and reads its result before it can decide the next, so gathering context command-by-command spends a sequential turn on each and the turns dominate the wall clock. Yoink collapses that. One plan carries every command whose form is fixed before its result, runs them together, and returns a single bundle the role reasons over once, so many round-trips become one. Latency is the reason the discipline is absolute rather than a preference.
+
+Yoink earns its place even on a lone command: it captures each command's stdout, stderr, exit status, and timing as separate labelled parts, so the role reads a clean structured result instead of a shell's mixed and truncated output. So a single retrieval runs through Yoink too; batching many round-trips into one is the further win on top of that, not the only reason to use it.
+
+So every file read, directory listing, search, tooling probe, version check, dry-run, coverage run, and test run goes inside a Yoink plan and executes through `npx @dk/yoink`, and the role reasons from the one bundle it returns. A bare `cat`, `ls`, `find`, `grep`, `git`, `npm`, `npx`, or file read issued outside a Yoink plan is a fault, no matter the reason. Batch everything decidable together into one plan; run a further plan only where a later command depends on an earlier plan's result. Writing and editing files uses the write and edit tools; that is the only work that is not a Yoink plan. Yoink is always present, so no role reaches for shell as a fallback.
+
 ### Dispositions
 
 1. **Durable artifacts outrank chat.** Binding product behaviour lives in valid `.feature` files. `assets/**` are human-owned product material under Captain custody; the Asset policy carries the rules. Conversation context is discarded; when chat and a durable artifact disagree, the artifact wins. `CAPTAIN.md`, if present, contains Captain-only non-binding notes. `AGENTS.md` and `RIGGING.md` are tooling configuration, not product intent; the Project configuration section carries their shapes.
